area_description_data.1: This is considered the best and most exclusive residential district in Phoenix. The northern half is known as Encanto and the southern half as Palmcroft. This was the last subdivision created before the depression. Houses therein range in price from $7,000 to $15,000, some higher. The area is highly restricted. It is occupied by the more affluent business and professional men.
This area closely resembles A-1 as to the grades of security, but is probably not as highly restricted.

This is the oldest of the best residential sections of Phoenix and is still considered among the very best in the city. Within this area are some large and high-priced homes, some ranging in age between twenty-five years and thirty years. Prominent business and professional people live in this area.

The eastern portion of this is the newest subdivision in Phoenix now under development. It is known as Country Club Manor. Houses therein range in cost from $7,500 to $40,000. The area is well planned and highly restricted. The two strips on 7th Street and East Thomas Road are known as the Country Club Drive sections, very exclusive as to types of construction and restrictions. Houses in this area are all less than fifteen years old, most of them less than ten years old.

This small area compares favorably with the Country. Club section across the street to the east. Within it there is room for some development, all of which will be in the very best type of construction.

This is the newest and best moderately priced residential section of Phoenix, and within it there has been considerable new construction during the last few months. The area is less than fifteen years old and is occupied by modest business and professional people. Cost of construction in the area ranges from $3,500 to $6,500.

That portion of this area lying within the city limits contains some very fine homes averaging $6,000 in price. Without the city limits the construction is cheaper. This is a substantial residential section occupied by a good class of citizenry. Indications are that there will be considerable development in this area in the future.

This area is entirely outside the city limits, but is in line with the trend of development. The security is not as costly as that of B-1 and B-2, ranging in price from $2,000 to $7,000. Lack of city restrictions in this area is perhaps counteracted by lower taxes.

This is a very substantial section wherein the houses are from ten to fifteen years old and the average price range is $3,250. The area has advantages as to school and mercantile facilities, being reasonably close to the business district; also transportation. Business and professional people occupy the area.

This is a well located, moderately priced subdivision, occupied by tradesmen and modest business and professional people. Much of the security therein was built for speculative purposes. The western portion of it was built up twenty years ago, while the eastern half is as new as eight years.

This section, lying without the city limits, has a large number of smaller homes of the modest class of people, ranging in price from $1,200 to $2,500. There is room for much development and indications are that there will be some building in this section.

This area lies outside the city limits, and, while it is considered a good residential section, the security hardly compares with that of adjoining B-4. Modest homes, ranging from $1,200 to $2,250, in this area are occupied by suburban dwellers of the moderate class. The district was created about twelve years ago.

This area is sparsely settled, but contains a few good homes and some of the cheaper type. It is outside the city limits, and the district will likely see some development in the near future and its value may be enhanced by reason of the exclusive development in the adjoining Country Club Manor.

This area is only partially developed. It has several advantages of the in-town sections, including sewer, water, gas, etc., but of course does not have the restrictions of the city proper. Suburban dwellers occupy this area in houses ranging in price from $1,200 to $6,000. There is some new building in progress in this area, with prospects of much more new construction. Prospects are that the Indian School Road will be the city limits of Phoenix after the next expansion.

This is one of the older residential sections of Phoenix, and is declining because of obsolescence and business encroachment. Houses in this section are as old as forty
 
 years, but the property is readily rentable because of the proximity to the business district.

This is known as Churchill Addition. Although this area has reached its peak as to values and is declining as a choice residential section, it nevertheless has many advantages, such as school facilities and. proximity to the business district. There are many of the nicer homes in the eastern portion of this area, but in that portion lying between Polk and Roosevelt and 1st and 7th Streets are many of the older houses of Phoenix. This area is occupied by a modest working class of people.

This is Capitol Addition. Restrictions imposed more than twenty-five years ago have expired. The area has an advantage because of the location of the State Capitol, but has reached its peak in development. Houses therein are as old as forty years.
This small area, situated near railroad shops and. industrial development is old and contains a very poor security. It is occupied entirely by working people.
This is an old section of Phoenix, adjacent to the business and industrial sections of the city, occupied entirely by a poor class of working people. The security is ragged.

This section, adjoining the railroad station and yards, is a semi-industrial section, with very poor houses.
 
 Negroes, Mexicans and different classes of foreigners are rapidly occupying this area.

This section, lying outside the city limits, is very
 
 ragged, occupied by Mexicans, Negroes and the low class of white people. There is no sale for property herein.

This wide area, all outside the city limits, is occupied by low salaried working people, but the district has suffered no encroachment by Negroes, Mexicans, etc. Most of the houses therein are small frame houses, but the surroundings are well kept. There is a good school in the area. This district will continue to be occupied by a hard working class of people with low incomes.

In the Negro section are some very good homes, considering their occupancy by colored people. Other houses in the area are cheap. There is within this area a mixed occupancy, including Mexicans, foreigners, etc.
This area, outside the city limits, contains a number of reasonably good small homes of working people, but is without prospects of development.

This area resembles D-3 in every respect, being occupied largely by Mexicans, Negroes, and the lower classes of white working people. The security is old and poor.
 
 The area suffers from its proximity to the railroad yards and other industrial development.
